[{"id":"VR834531","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows two equipotential lines between two parallel vertical plates. The plate on the left is labeled A and has a potential of 0 volts. The plate on the right is labeled B and has a potential of negative 6 volts. Two equipotential lines are indicated at regularly spaced intervals between the two plates, and from left to right are labeled negative 2 volts and negative 4 volts respectively.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR834531.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A uniform electric field is present between two parallel plates, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span>, as represented by the equipotential lines shown in the figure. Particle <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M\"><math alttext=\"M\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>M</mi></math></span></span> and charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>Q</mi></math></span></span> is released from rest from Plate <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span> and travels in a straight line until it reaches Plate <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span>. Next, Particle <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2 M\"><math alttext=\"2 M\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn><mi>M</mi></math></span></span> and the same charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>Q</mi></math></span></span> is released from rest from Plate <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span>. Particle <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> also travels in a straight line until it reaches Plate <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span>. Which of the following correctly indicates whether the final speeds of the two particles are equal, and provides evidence or reasoning to support the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR834531_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Yes, the speeds are equal. The particles experience the same force and therefore have the same acceleration.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Yes, the speeds are equal. The particles experience the same force over the same distance.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">No, the speeds are not equal. The particles have different masses and therefore have different amounts of kinetic energy at Plate <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span>.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">No, the speeds are not equal. The particles have the same kinetic energy at Plate <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span>, but have different masses.</p>"],"answer":3}]